<p>
  Every photo taken with a camera or smartphone contains hidden information — called metadata — that records when, where, and how the photo was taken. This guide explains what image metadata is and how to view it for free.
</p>

<h2>What is Image Metadata?</h2>

<p>Image metadata is data embedded inside the image file that is not part of the visual content itself. There are two main types:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Basic metadata:</strong> File name, file size, dimensions, color mode, MIME type, and last modified date. Available for all image types.</li>
  <li><strong>EXIF metadata:</strong> Camera-specific data embedded by JPEG files from cameras and phones. Includes camera make and model, lens focal length, aperture (f-stop), ISO speed, shutter speed, capture date and time, and GPS coordinates.</li>
</ul>

