<h2>Common EXIF Fields Explained</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Camera Make / Model:</strong> The manufacturer and model of the camera (e.g., "Apple iPhone 15 Pro").</li>
  <li><strong>Date Taken:</strong> The exact date and time the shutter was pressed.</li>
  <li><strong>Focal Length:</strong> The zoom level used (e.g., 24mm = wide, 200mm = telephoto).</li>
  <li><strong>F-Number:</strong> Aperture setting. Lower f-stop = more background blur (bokeh).</li>
  <li><strong>ISO Speed:</strong> Sensor sensitivity. Higher ISO = brighter in low light, more grain.</li>
  <li><strong>Exposure Time:</strong> Shutter speed (e.g., 1/500s = fast, 1/30s = slow). Fast shutter freezes motion; slow shutter blurs it.</li>
  <li><strong>GPS Latitude / Longitude:</strong> The coordinates where the photo was taken, if location services were active.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Privacy Considerations</h2>

<p>
  If you share photos publicly, EXIF GPS data reveals exactly where a photo was taken — including your home address if you photographed something inside. Always check for GPS data before sharing photos publicly. You can strip EXIF data by re-exporting through the <a href="/imagewonder/image-converter">Image Converter</a> — the canvas export does not write EXIF headers.
</p>

<h2>View EXIF Data on Desktop</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Windows:</strong> Right-click the image → Properties → Details tab. Shows all embedded EXIF fields.</li>
  <li><strong>Mac:</strong> Open in Preview → Tools → Show Inspector → EXIF tab.</li>
  <li><strong>Linux:</strong> <code>exiftool filename.jpg</code> (install via package manager).</li>
</ul>

